{
    "text": "Step at a time",
    "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:57:12 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "One kind of skill involves simply following the steps, with each step being not very difficult. If the steps are carried out in good order, something rather complex can come into being, even though nothing very difficult was being done at any given moment.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:57:22 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145722"
        },
        {
            "text": "The recipe for caramelized onion dal, for example, in the cookbook <a href=\"https://www.prairielightsbooks.com/book/9781328482471\">Indian-ish</a>, is like that.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:57:32 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145732"
        },
        {
            "text": "Measure the ingredients. Urad dal, from the Indian grocery, kosher salt, turmeric, lime juice, olive oil, a sliced onion, ghee or olive oil, cumin seeds, four dried red chiles, chili powder, and optional asafetida.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:57:42 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145742"
        },
        {
            "text": "Cook the dal with salt, turmeric and water in a skillet for a while. When it's done, add lime juice.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:57:52 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145752"
        },
        {
            "text": "In another pan, simmer the onions in the oil slowly, turning frequently, until they're caramelized.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:59:02 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145902"
        },
        {
            "text": "In a small pan, warm the ghee (or use oil), sizzle the cumin seeds for a few seconds, remove from the heat, add the chiles, the chili powder, and the asafetida. Stir.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:59:12 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145912"
        },
        {
            "text": "Put some cooked basmati rice in a large bowl (white). Put the dal on top (yellow). Drizzle the spicy oil over the top. Spread the caramelized onions over the top (crunchy brown). Arrange the four chilis over the top decoratively (bright red).",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:59:22 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145922"
        },
        {
            "text": "Not a step was difficult. Took about an hour. The result is fabulous and the flavors are complex.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:59:32 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145932"
        },
        {
            "text": "Some good things in life are that way.",
            "created": "Sat, 27 Aug 2022 14:59:42 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/27/145712.html?title=stepAtATime#a145942"
        }
    ]
}

description:
When two dozen or more FBI agents searched former President Donald Trump’s residence three weeks ago, most Americans initially were left wondering what in the world must Trump have done.&nbsp;After all, a prodigious FBI search logically indicates an equally prodigious violation of some federal statute; therefore, it must be really serious.&nbsp;One former Department of Justice (DOJ) official told Politico that the evidence sought&nbsp;“was likely so pulverizing in its force”&nbsp;that it would “eviscerate” the possibility of the optics for such an invasive law enforcement action not being good.



Well, it’s now pretty official: The optics aren’t good.



Everyone in America, from plumber to president, is constitutionally protected from a government search that lacks adequate cause.&nbsp;&nbsp;



We now know why the DOJ wanted the affidavit — which is supposed to articulate the probable cause needed for a legitimate search — to be kept under seal.&nbsp;After the magistrate who authorized the search forced the DOJ to unseal&nbsp;a redacted version, two realities came into better focus.



First, the affidavit confirmed that the FBI’s investigation was triggered in January 2022 at the request of the National Archives which wanted certain documents, especially classified documents, that it considered to be presidential records to be turned over to it by Trump. Second, from what I have seen, I don’t believe the affidavit articulates how a federal law was or is being broken.&nbsp;For those who hold out hope that the affidavit’s redacted sections fill that gap, there is almost no chance that they do. (More on that below.)&nbsp;



As to the first point, this matter is, as suspected, nothing more than a document dispute that was chugging along, appropriately, as a negotiation behind the scenes and apparently making some progress.&nbsp;I don’t see anything in the affidavit asserting a refusal by Trump to cooperate.&nbsp;



Any clinging hope — in certain quarters — that the affidavit possessed “pulverizing” cause to believe Trump was engaged in a truly serious federal violation can — I think — be considered dashed.&nbsp;The pipe dream that Trump was engaged in espionage, actively providing secrets to an enemy I think is as fanciful as the Steele dossier’s&nbsp;Moscow&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;bed reverie. And, no, I don’t believe a smoking gun of espionage or something equally shocking will be in the redacted sections.&nbsp;If the FBI had that, it would have fronted that in the unredacted portions.&nbsp;&nbsp;



As to the second and more important point, the affidavit’s probable cause statements focus on only half of what is needed to show a possible violation of the federal statutes that are cited in the warrant.&nbsp;The affidavit does a reasonable job of establishing cause to believe Trump possessed a range of classified materials — or at least once-classified materials — and that those materials were located in his residence.



But that’s not all that’s needed — in this case in particular. A criminal violation of those statutes only exists if it can be established that the person being investigated was not authorized to possess, store, transfer or copy those documents. This is an easy element to establish against anyone in America. Except one person.  



The unredacted parts of the affidavit make no attempt to articulate cause that Trump was not authorized to have these documents in his home.&nbsp;The reason why is that, as president, he had&nbsp;broad, legally intimidating authority, established by law and court determinations, to declassify any and all documents and to determine what is and is not a presidential record.&nbsp;Trump and his legal team have asserted that this authority was exercised while he was still president. Therefore, a violation of these fairly low-level and seldom-prosecuted document-oriented statutes cannot be proven.&nbsp;&nbsp;



I don’t think there’s much chance that the affidavit’s redacted portions contain some novel legal theory undercutting this broad, well-established presidential authority.&nbsp;Affidavits for intrusive searches of a private home — the most extreme action the government can take against a resident of the United States, short of arrest — are not the place for advancing theories.&nbsp;Probable cause must be built on facts.&nbsp;



The redacted sections are considerable.&nbsp;Redaction is supposed to be utilized only to protect sensitive methods and techniques — in other words, how the government came by its information that it doesn’t want to publicly divulge so it can keep using those tactics or protect providers of information.&nbsp;A good and prudent example would be the use of confidential human and/or technical sources.&nbsp;A bad example would be citing press reports, a la the&nbsp;Carter Page FISA affidavit.



The redacted portions therefore, normally, will simply cover how the FBI supported its assertions in the unredacted sections that Trump possessed classified materials in his residence — i.e., what confidential or sensitive sources were used to establish those facts.&nbsp;Don’t expect anything more.&nbsp;



The situation does not look good for the government.&nbsp;The Ivy League-educated attorneys of the DOJ had to know this adventure had little chance of an eventual successful prosecution. The use, therefore, of a highly intrusive search of a home simply as a forcing function to retrieve documents for the National Archives — and&nbsp;then&nbsp;not follow through with actual charges — spikes the potential abuse needle dramatically and will not help quiet the growing suspicion that this was more of&nbsp;a political hit-job to take Trump off the chessboard than it was the pursuit of blind justice.&nbsp;&nbsp;



I am often asked if the FBI had no choice but to pursue the National Archives request and open a case.&nbsp;Yes, it had a choice and, no, it didn’t have to&nbsp;open this investigation.&nbsp;The FBI declines to initiate cases involving more serious violations all the time.&nbsp;&nbsp;



The platitudinous justification from Democrats is “No one is above the law” — but we know that’s not true. The last time the Democrats controlled the DOJ, Hillary Clinton was set high aloft and placed out of reach of “reasonable” prosecution by then-FBI director James Comey with the concurrence of the DOJ. Even Comey noted that she was clearly not authorized to possess highly classified documents on a private server.



Politicians on both the right and left say bombastic things that inflame passions and drive opposition attempts to eliminate competition. But involving our justice system in politically tainted efforts can never be tolerated.  No citizen of this land, no matter who they are, should be subjected to a law enforcement action where there is an absence of evidence that anything illegal occurred.



Kevin R. Brock is a former assistant director of intelligence for the FBI and principal deputy director of the&nbsp;National Counterterrorism Center&nbsp;(NCTC). He independently consults with private companies and public-safety agencies on strategic mission technologies.

Four organizations representing European judges filed a lawsuit Sunday against the Council of the EU over its decision to greenlight Poland’s recovery plan despite ongoing rule-of-law concerns.&nbsp;



The judges’ groups argue that the Council approved Warsaw’s Recovery and Resilience Plan in a way that disregards judgments from the Court of Justice of the EU and harms both Polish judges and the European judiciary system.



In June, the Council signed off on a plan that could allow Poland to access billions in coronavirus recovery funds if it meets a set of “milestones,” including reforming a controversial disciplinary regime for judges. And while Warsaw has yet to receive funds under the plan, the blueprint itself is now being challenged.&nbsp;



The four organizations suing the Council — the European Association of Judges, the Association of European Administrative Judges, Judges for Judges and MEDEL, an association representing European judges and prosecutors — said that the plan’s targets are problematic.&nbsp;&nbsp;



“These milestones fall short of what is required to ensure effective protection of the independence of judges and the judiciary and disregard the judgments of the CJEU on the matter,” the groups wrote in a statement.&nbsp;



The Court of Justice, the organizations note, “has ruled that the Polish judges affected by unlawful disciplinary procedures should be reinstated at once, without delay or a procedure, while the third milestone would introduce a procedure of more than a year with an uncertain outcome.”&nbsp;



The lawsuit’s aim is in part to prevent Poland from accessing funds until it complies with court rulings.&nbsp;



“The reason for asking the annulment of the EU Council’s decision is to make explicit the principle that judgments of the CJEU on the subject of the independence of judiciaries should be enforced without delay and in full,” the judges said. The “Council decision violates this principle, because there is no full — i.e. unconditional — enforcement of CJEU judgments,” they added.



The Good Lobby Profs, an academic-led initiative which provided support for the legal action, said in its own statement that the European Commission and the Council of the EU have both breached their duties when it comes to the Polish plan. The Commission and the Council have a duty, the group said, “not to treat judgments of the Court of Justice as bargaining chips and adjustment variables for reasons of political convenience.”&nbsp;

outlineJsontext:
{
    "text": "Our narrow training",
    "created": "Sun, 28 Aug 2022 15:47:19 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "In a short posting that <a href=\"https://twitter.com/moritz\">Moritz F. Fürst</a> calls <a href=\"https://moritzfuerst.net/texts/arts-of-noticing\">a parable</a>, we learn about some of the mundane episodes in the work of EMT or ambulance workers. Some calls for an ambulance are episodes of crisis, but many others appear to be little more than routine acts of transportation. He examines the ways workers think and talk about the mundane parts of their work, which sparked a series of thoughts here.",
            "created": "Sun, 28 Aug 2022 15:56:36 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a155636"
        },
        {
            "text": "I once served on our university's Information Technology committee, where faculty members were meant to guide the IT department in its service of the teaching and research work being done on campus. Over time I gathered the impression that the IT director thought the university's computer network would be just about perfect if only she could keep humans from touching any part of it. In those years, there was a professor who was said to keep his coffee cup on the slid-open cd-rom drive of his office computer, so I could understand a certain amount of frustration on the director's part with human beings using the gear. Still, as I reflect upon Moritz's essay or parable, I remind myself that our expertise is sterile if it hopes to exclude the humanity of those we are supposed to serve.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:11:10 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a151110"
        },
        {
            "text": "In different fields, you hear stories of professionals trying to remind themselves of this vital insight, and trying to train newcomers to understand it. Medical schools sometimes ask students to read literary works by Chekhov, W.C. Williams, Coles, eg., for that purpose.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:13:18 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a151318"
        },
        {
            "text": "At a military museum once, I photographed all the places on large pieces of artillery that were meant to be held or operated by a human hand. After about an hour of doing so, having located places all over the equipment meant to be held or squeezed or pushed or pulled by the soldiers, I had the feeling of a ghostly presence of soldiers moving ant-like all over and around and under the artillery pieces. A chilling thought came to me that piece of equipment relentlessly trains up a person into being a part of the machine, even part of a killing machine.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:16:21 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a151621"
        },
        {
            "text": "Many things in our training try to sharpen us, to narrow us. Amazing skills can arise from that, as well as indifference or even blindnesses to other parts of life.",
            "created": "Sun, 28 Aug 2022 16:10:14 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a161014"
        },
        {
            "text": "Different things help us resist the narrowness of our training. Interdisciplinary study, where we learn the tools for seeing used by many fields, can help. The arts, which are about rejiggering our perceptions, our hearts and minds, can help. Identifying with the other person, which can be a psychological or spiritual practice, can help.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:17:56 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a151756"
        },
        {
            "text": "In academic fields, the opportunity to write not just about the tools of the field, but about the field's human context as well, seems vital, though this may not be common. Moritz's essay is an important example.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:20:31 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a152031"
        },
        {
            "text": "His essay acknowledges that a technician must not pretend there are no emotions in doing the work. Must not pretend that there is no boredom, no anger, say, for the technician, or no emotional need being felt by the medical patient, eg.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:24:01 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a152401"
        },
        {
            "text": "In a tiny short story called \"<a href=\"https://theshortstory.co.uk/devsitegkl/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Short-stories-Wiliam-Carlos-Williams-The-Use-of-Force.pdf\">The Use of Force</a>,\" William Carlos Williams tells about a family doctor much like himself becoming angry with the parents who have delayed getting help for their child because they didn't have money to pay for it, and angry too at the frightened child who fights back against the doctor. Both things put the child at risk of a potentially fatal illness.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:24:51 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a152451"
        },
        {
            "text": "That doctor's desire to merely carry out the life-saving technical task is being thwarted, and the doctor sees his own emotions rising unprofessionally. At that moment, the practice of medicine is deeply interwoven in a very flawed but understandable humanity.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:27:58 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a152758"
        },
        {
            "text": "All of which is to say that reflections about the human context of one's profession, as in the essay or parable by Moritz, are very important. Much is at stake.",
            "created": "Sun Aug 28 15:28:35 +0000 2022",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/08/28/154719.html?title=ourNarrowTraining#a152835"
        }
    ]
}

